aaa

aa

abc

A variable is an object created with the tf.Variable() constructor, which has a value that persists across sessions. In the above code, we are creating a variable named numbers_var with a tensor of the input list. This will contain all the elements of the list as numbers. The tf.cast() method is used to convert the dtype of the variable to tf.float32.

The tf.reduce_mean() method calculates the mean of all the elements of the input tensor, which is the number in the list. The result is an object of type float32 and it will contain the output of the mean calculation.

The tf.reduce_mean() method has the following parameters:

axis (optional) – A Tensor. Must be one of the following types: int32, int64. Defaults to None.
    int32 or int64, 0 <= axis < rank(input). Describes which axis of the input Tensor to reduce across. For vectors, use axis = 0.
keep_dims (optional) – A bool. Defaults to False.
    If true, retain reduced dimensions with length 1.
The axis parameter specifies the dimension of the input tensor that we want to reduce along. If we don't pass a value for axis, it defaults to None, which is equivalent to passing -1, the last dimension of the input tensor. For this case, the tf.reduce_mean() method will reduce all the elements of the tensor, resulting in a scalar value.
